ong their skin, then disappears before it can drip.\n\nFurther ahead, another traveler moves with restless energy, shifting their weight, adjusting their pack, glancing at the sky as though trying to calculate an end that never arrives. Every few steps, they wipe their face with quick, irritated motions, as if the rain is something personal.\n\nNo one speaks.\n\nAnd yet the silence is not empty.\n\nIt hums.\n\nLow and constant, beneath the sound of rain and footsteps and the soft grind of wheels. You feel it more than you hear it—a vibration somewhere in your chest, faint at first, then slowly growing more noticeable the longer you walk.\n\nYou try to locate its source.\n\nIt isn't coming from the ground.\n\nOr the sky.\n\nOr any single person.\n\nIt's everywhere.\n\nYou adjust your pace, moving closer to the center of the caravan. The shapes begin to resolve into details: a wagon draped in layered fabric that shifts color subtly depending on the angle of the light; a cluster of travelers walking close together, their movements unconsciously synchronized; a figure seated near the back of a cart, head bowed, hands resting on their belly beneath heavy cloth.\n\nThere is a stillness around that one.\n\nNot the stillness of absence.\n\nThe stillness of something gathering.\n\nYou don't stare. Not directly. But you feel it—the way the space around them seems to bend slightly, as though the rain itself moves differently in their presence. Slower. Thicker. More deliberate.\n\nSomeone nearby walks beside the cart, one hand resting lightly against its side. Not gripping. Not guiding. Just there. Present.\n\nHolding.\n\nYou look away, unsure why the sight unsettles you.\n\nThe road shifts.\n\nNot visibly at first. Just a subtle change in how your body responds. The ground feels less predictable beneath your feet, the pull of the mud more uneven, as if something beneath the surface is moving in slow, patient currents.\n\nA flicker of light cuts across the sky.\n\nNot lightning